49
00:03:54,526 --> 00:03:56,152
<i>Whoa, whoa, whoa</i>

50
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:58,029
<i>She's a lady</i>

51
00:03:58,738 --> 00:04:01,825
<i>Talkin' about that little lady</i>

52
00:04:02,701 --> 00:04:03,785
<i>-And the...</i>
-(MUSIC STOPS)

53
00:04:03,868 --> 00:04:05,954
-Thank you so much, Waldo.
-But...

54
00:04:06,037 --> 00:04:07,747
-Please, take a seat, that was...
-Wait, but I'm...

55
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:09,416
Nope, take a seat. Thank you very much.

56
00:04:09,499 --> 00:04:11,292
-That was, uh...
-(KNOCK AT DOOR)

57
00:04:11,710 --> 00:04:13,461
Unique. That was very unique.

58
00:04:14,504 --> 00:04:17,007
Hold your horses, I'm coming.

59
00:04:17,507 --> 00:04:18,842
Oh. Hello.

60
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:22,220
And what can I do for you two?

61
00:04:22,303 --> 00:04:26,099
Stymie has to come home.
Our daddy broke two of his legs.

62
00:04:26,182 --> 00:04:28,560
Two of his legs? Oh, my.

63
00:04:28,643 --> 00:04:32,022
Mary Ann has to come, too.
Her mama's havin' a baby.

64
00:04:32,397 --> 00:04:34,232
A baby? Since when?

65
00:04:34,315 --> 00:04:35,400
BUCKWHEAT: Since this morning.

66
00:04:35,483 --> 00:04:37,569
She found out about it
and now she's having it.

67
00:04:38,153 --> 00:04:42,949
And my mama says Spanky and Alfalfa have
to come home right away.

68
00:04:43,241 --> 00:04:44,951
Right away? Why?

69
00:04:45,201 --> 00:04:47,120
It's important business.

70
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:49,873
Oh. What's the important business?

71
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:52,667
Beats me. That's what Spanky told me to say.

72
00:04:52,751 --> 00:04:53,835
Right, Spank?

73
00:04:54,002 --> 00:04:55,378
(STUDENTS LAUGH)

74
00:04:58,715 --> 00:05:02,552
Spanky, Alfalfa, Stymie,
Mary Ann, get up here right away.

75
00:05:03,970 --> 00:05:05,347
KID 1: They're in trouble.

76
00:05:07,432 --> 00:05:09,017
Something important has come up

77
00:05:09,100 --> 00:05:11,770
and you all need to go home right away.

78
00:05:13,146 --> 00:05:16,066
Well, Miss Crabtree, it's been a real great year.

79
00:05:16,149 --> 00:05:17,567
Yeah, have a good summer, Miss Crabtree.

80
00:05:17,650 --> 00:05:18,985
See ya next year.

81
00:05:19,069 --> 00:05:20,487
Don't take any wooden nickels.

82
00:05:21,071 --> 00:05:22,113
Ah.

83
00:05:22,864 --> 00:05:23,948
Beep, beep.

84
00:05:24,032 --> 00:05:26,201
Miss Crabtree, I've got your ice cream cake.

85
00:05:26,284 --> 00:05:27,827
-Oh, yes, bring it right in.
-(STUDENTS GASP)

86
00:05:28,536 --> 00:05:30,497
(STUDENTS EXCLAIM IN AWE)

87
00:05:32,540 --> 00:05:35,460
All right, boys and girls,
I have a little surprise.

88
00:05:35,543 --> 00:05:37,504
We're not gonna do any more work today.

89
00:05:37,587 --> 00:05:40,090
Instead, we're gonna have
an end-of-the-year party

90
00:05:40,173 --> 00:05:42,676
with a great big ice cream cake.

91
00:05:42,759 --> 00:05:44,135
(STUDENTS CHEERING)

92
00:05:44,552 --> 00:05:47,806
You know, Miss Crabtree,
I think our folks can wait a little while.

93
00:05:48,306 --> 00:05:52,477
Yeah! My mom's had babies before.
I'm sure she knows what to do.

94
00:05:53,269 --> 00:05:56,022
My daddy isn't goin' anywhere. He can't.

95
00:05:56,523 --> 00:05:57,691
His legs are broke.

96
00:05:58,233 --> 00:05:59,567
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

97
00:05:59,651 --> 00:06:02,529
You can't keep
your families waiting just for a party.

98
00:06:02,612 --> 00:06:04,989
Now run along now
and I will see you next fall.

99
00:06:05,073 --> 00:06:06,116
(STUDENTS PROTESTING)

100
00:06:06,199 --> 00:06:08,535
-No, please.
-Run along. See you next fall.

101
00:06:08,618 --> 00:06:10,620
-She had them before.
-Oh.

102
00:06:10,704 --> 00:06:12,539
You kids don't know what you're missing.

103
00:06:12,622 --> 00:06:13,832
Who wants cake?

104
00:06:13,915 --> 00:06:15,750
ALL: Me!

105
00:06:18,253 --> 00:06:21,214
Oh, man. Did you see that cake?

106
00:06:21,297 --> 00:06:24,092
Not just a cake, an ice cream cake.

107
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:26,678
Yeah, ice cream and cake.

108
00:06:26,928 --> 00:06:30,348
The two best
things in the world all mixed together.

109
00:06:30,432 --> 00:06:32,517
Too many calories, men.

110
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:35,395
And you all
could stand to lose a few pounds anyway.

111
00:06:36,146 --> 00:06:37,188
Mmm.

112
00:06:37,272 --> 00:06:38,940
Man, that cake was good.

113
00:06:39,024 --> 00:06:40,608
You said it, pal.

114
00:06:40,817 --> 00:06:43,069
No time to dwell on the past, men.

115
00:06:43,153 --> 00:06:45,947
Summer vacation has officially begun.

116
00:06:46,448 --> 00:06:50,702
No school, no homework, no getting up early.

117
00:06:50,785 --> 00:06:54,289
-We're free. Come on, time's a-wastin'.
-All right!

118
00:06:54,372 --> 00:06:55,665
-(BARKING)
-BUCKWHEAT: Whoo-hoo!

119
00:06:57,751 --> 00:06:59,002
Hi!

120
00:06:59,461 --> 00:07:01,588
-SPANKY: Hiya, Pops!
-Hi there. Hi.

121
00:07:08,303 --> 00:07:09,471
SPANKY: Yay!

122
00:07:12,140 --> 00:07:13,183
Oh!

123
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:17,854
-Kids! (SCOFFS) Watch where you're going.
-STYMIE: Sorry.

124
00:07:17,937 --> 00:07:20,190
-Sorry, Officer Kennedy.
-Wait a minute.

125
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:22,233
Aren't you kids supposed to be in school?

126
00:07:22,317 --> 00:07:24,903
We got time off for good behavior.

127
00:07:24,986 --> 00:07:26,404
That would be a first.

128
00:07:26,488 --> 00:07:29,574
So who are the flowers for? Miss Crabtree?

129
00:07:29,657 --> 00:07:31,409
ALL: Yeah!

130
00:07:31,493 --> 00:07:32,535
They were.

131
00:07:32,619 --> 00:07:34,120
When are you finally gonna work up

132
00:07:34,204 --> 00:07:36,206
the nerve to ask her to marry you?

133
00:07:36,289 --> 00:07:39,751
I will, I will.
When school's out and the time's right,

134
00:07:39,834 --> 00:07:41,211
I'll be ready.

135
00:07:41,294 --> 00:07:43,546
I got the ring. Finally paid it off.

136
00:07:44,547 --> 00:07:45,590
-ALL: Ooh!
-Ah, ah, ah, ah, ah!

137
00:07:45,757 --> 00:07:48,468
Look, don't touch. You understand?

138
00:07:48,551 --> 00:07:51,638
Isn't there supposed to be a diamond on it?

139
00:07:53,807 --> 00:07:57,560
Oh, there it is.
It looks real nice when you can see it.

140
00:07:57,644 --> 00:08:00,647
-Well, good luck, Officer Kennedy.
-Thank you.

141
00:08:00,730 --> 00:08:03,316
Try not to blow it. Come on, guys.

142
00:08:06,903 --> 00:08:08,238
(CHEERING)

143
00:08:12,117 --> 00:08:13,868
SPANKY: To the bakery!

144
00:08:20,250 --> 00:08:21,710
Hiya, Grandma.

145
00:08:21,793 --> 00:08:23,712
Oh, hi, kids. Oh, hi!

146
00:08:24,212 --> 00:08:25,630
ALL: Hi, Grandma.

147
00:08:25,964 --> 00:08:28,550
Oh, boy. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

148
00:08:29,843 --> 00:08:35,265
Oh, so, isn't there still
one more day left at school?

149
00:08:35,849 --> 00:08:39,936
They never do
anything important on the last day.

150
00:08:40,437 --> 00:08:42,564
Except eat ice cream cake.

151
00:08:42,647 --> 00:08:46,317
Okay. I don't suppose
I could interest you in cinnamon muffins.

152
00:08:46,568 --> 00:08:48,236
Yeah!

153
00:08:48,319 --> 00:08:50,071
GRANDMA: Here we go.
STYMIE: Me, Grandma!

154
00:08:57,328 --> 00:08:58,830
I caught it!

155
00:08:59,122 --> 00:09:01,916
Thanks, Grandma. You are the best.

156
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:04,794
ALL: Yeah! Thanks, Grandma!

157
00:09:04,919 --> 00:09:07,172
-(BARKING)
-I didn't forget you.

158
00:09:08,465 --> 00:09:11,509
Come on, gang. To the tree house!

159
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:13,261
(CHEERING)

160
00:09:13,345 --> 00:09:14,596
STYMIE: See you later, Grandma.

161
00:09:16,056 --> 00:09:17,891
-After you, Petey.
-(ALFALFA LAUGHS)

162
00:09:19,309 --> 00:09:21,227
SPANKY: Home, sweet home.

163
00:09:21,311 --> 00:09:22,354
ALFALFA: Mmm-hmm.

164
00:09:22,437 --> 00:09:24,230
SPANKY: Petey, do your stuff.

165
00:09:43,500 --> 00:09:44,751
(WHINES)

166
00:09:59,724 --> 00:10:00,725
(SCHOOL BELL RINGS)

167
00:10:00,809 --> 00:10:01,810
(KIDS CHEERING)

168
00:10:02,686 --> 00:10:05,188
Whoa! No! No, no, no!

169
00:10:09,192 --> 00:10:10,360
Kids.

170
00:10:13,071 --> 00:10:14,989
Are they gone, Miss Crabtree?

171
00:10:15,490 --> 00:10:17,325
Oh, they are indeed, Officer Kennedy.

172
00:10:17,867 --> 00:10:19,327
And now that they are,

173
00:10:19,411 --> 00:10:21,579
I think that we
can call each other by our first names,

174
00:10:21,663 --> 00:10:22,914
Ed.

175
00:10:23,289 --> 00:10:24,958
-Of course, June.
-(CHUCKLES)

176
00:10:26,126 --> 00:10:27,419
What are those?

177
00:10:27,836 --> 00:10:29,004
Oh. Uh...

178
00:10:29,087 --> 00:10:31,798
They were flowers,
till your kids got a hold of them.

179
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:33,091
Thank you.

180
00:10:33,466 --> 00:10:35,218
It's the thought that counts.

181
00:10:35,301 --> 00:10:36,886
(SNIFFS) Mmm.

182
00:10:36,970 --> 00:10:39,556
I was thinking,
maybe you and I could have lunch

183
00:10:39,639 --> 00:10:42,892
at this very special place
that I happen to know of?

184
00:10:42,976 --> 00:10:45,937
A date with my man. Why, I'd love to.

185
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:47,522
Oh.

186
00:10:48,565 --> 00:10:51,359
ALFALFA: (WARMING UP VOICE)
Me, me, me, me, me, me, me.

187
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:55,030
Me, me, me, me, me.

188
00:10:55,238 --> 00:10:56,281
Me.

189
00:10:59,868 --> 00:11:00,910
Ready, gang?

190
00:11:01,036 --> 00:11:02,495
-Yeah!
-Ready!

191
00:11:02,579 --> 00:11:03,705
Ready, indeed.

192
00:11:03,747 --> 00:11:05,832
Hi, ladies and gentlemen.

193
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:08,418
Tonight, we're going to perform an oldie,
but a goodie

194
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:10,337
called <i>I Got You, Babe.</i>

195
00:11:10,754 --> 00:11:13,089
My name is Spanky and we are

196
00:11:13,173 --> 00:11:16,593
the International Silver String
Submarine Band.

197
00:11:16,676 --> 00:11:17,677
Huh?

198
00:11:17,761 --> 00:11:18,845
PORKY: The what?

199
00:11:18,928 --> 00:11:22,265
That's our band name? Since when?

200
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:24,351
Since I just thought it up a second ago.

201
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:27,270
Makes us sound important.

202
00:11:27,771 --> 00:11:28,855
-Okay.
-I agree.

203
00:11:28,938 --> 00:11:30,940
Okay, I like it.

204
00:11:31,024 --> 00:11:33,860
And a one and a two and a three.

205
00:11:34,611 --> 00:11:35,695
(BARKING)

206
00:11:36,279 --> 00:11:37,906
(ALL PLAYING TUNELESSLY)

207
00:11:43,745 --> 00:11:45,789
Hello, Mrs. Larson.

208
00:11:46,456 --> 00:11:47,540
Hi.

209
00:11:47,916 --> 00:11:50,627
You're early today. Here you go.

210
00:11:50,710 --> 00:11:52,295
On the house, as usual.

211
00:11:52,379 --> 00:11:54,798
-What is that noise?
-That's the kids' band.

212
00:11:55,048 --> 00:11:56,132
Oh...

213
00:11:56,216 --> 00:11:59,636
Well, tell them to keep practicing.

214
00:11:59,761 --> 00:12:00,970
(LAUGHING)

215
00:12:01,137 --> 00:12:03,390
Oh, and you got
a certified letter here from the bank.

216
00:12:03,640 --> 00:12:04,724
Oh.

217
00:12:04,808 --> 00:12:05,934
Sign here.

218
00:12:10,438 --> 00:12:12,482
-Here you go.
-Thanks.

219
00:12:12,816 --> 00:12:13,817
Thank you!

220
00:12:13,942 --> 00:12:14,984
You're welcome.

221
00:12:15,110 --> 00:12:16,569
They'll get better.

222
00:12:16,653 --> 00:12:18,279
I hope so.

223
00:12:18,321 --> 00:12:19,322
(GROANS)

224
00:12:19,447 --> 00:12:20,448
(LAUGHS)

225
00:12:26,496 --> 00:12:28,331
Oh. Oh.

226
00:12:31,334 --> 00:12:33,837
Hold it. Hold it. Why'd you stop?

227
00:12:33,962 --> 00:12:36,673
We were just
getting to the best part, where I sing.

228
00:12:36,798 --> 00:12:39,759
We're supposed to be playing,<i>
I Got You, Babe.</i>

229
00:12:39,843 --> 00:12:42,679
It sounds more like, <i>I Got a Headache, Babe.</i>

230
00:12:42,804 --> 00:12:44,472
What's wrong with everybody?

231
00:12:44,514 --> 00:12:46,474
We're doing the best we can, Spank.

232
00:12:46,516 --> 00:12:48,852
You know, he's right.

233
00:12:48,935 --> 00:12:52,605
Our music lacks a certain <i>je ne sais quoi.</i>

234
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:54,774
Like what?

235
00:12:54,858 --> 00:12:58,194
Like a girl singer.
That would complete our sound.

236
00:12:58,319 --> 00:13:00,989
And I know the perfect girl.

237
00:13:01,698 --> 00:13:03,366
Let me guess, Darla.

238
00:13:03,450 --> 00:13:04,492
SPANKY: Not again.

239
00:13:04,534 --> 00:13:06,161
-Great minds think alike.
-(SPANKY GROANS)

240
00:13:06,202 --> 00:13:09,664
You've heard her sing in class before.
She's really good.

241
00:13:09,706 --> 00:13:11,833
No girls allowed in the gang.

242
00:13:11,875 --> 00:13:14,836
But Mary Ann's in the gang. And she's a girl.

243
00:13:14,878 --> 00:13:17,047
I meant a real girl.

244
00:13:18,715 --> 00:13:20,884
I am a real girl.

245
00:13:21,009 --> 00:13:23,386
Okay. Okay. You're a real girl.

246
00:13:25,388 --> 00:13:27,974
Kids? Kids.

247
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:30,226
What is it, Grandma?

248
00:13:30,352 --> 00:13:31,895
Would you all watch the bakery for me?

249
00:13:31,978 --> 00:13:35,023
Something urgent came up
and I've gotta go to the bank.

250
00:13:35,065 --> 00:13:37,359
-What's wrong, Grandma?
-Everything's fine.

251
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:40,236
You just watch the shop and I'll be back soon.

252
00:13:40,362 --> 00:13:44,574
Don't worry, Grandma.
I got everything under control.

253
00:13:44,657 --> 00:13:45,825
No problem.

254
00:13:48,578 --> 00:13:49,746
Hello?

255
00:13:50,246 --> 00:13:51,498
Anybody here?

256
00:13:52,415 --> 00:13:54,209
-SPANKY: Hi!
-Yes, ma'am. How may we help you?

257
00:13:54,668 --> 00:13:58,254
Is there somebody else
working here today who's a little older?

258
00:13:58,338 --> 00:14:02,092
Don't be fooled. We're older than we look.

259
00:14:02,175 --> 00:14:03,760
Why, I'm nearly nine.

260
00:14:03,885 --> 00:14:07,347
-And our combined ages equal over 45.
-Mmm-hmm.

261
00:14:07,597 --> 00:14:13,186
And if you count, Petey, it's 103 in dog years.

262
00:14:13,770 --> 00:14:16,856
So, what can me
and my staff do you for today?

263
00:14:16,940 --> 00:14:20,568
I need a large birthday cake by 5:00.

264
00:14:20,694 --> 00:14:24,781
Don't worry. Our expert
bakers can have it ready for you in time.

265
00:14:24,864 --> 00:14:27,701
-What kind of cake do you want?
-Red velvet.

266
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:29,077
(GASPS)

267
00:14:29,786 --> 00:14:33,289
-You want a cake made out of velvet?
-Yuck!

268
00:14:33,373 --> 00:14:35,458
Yes, red velvet.

269
00:14:36,376 --> 00:14:39,462
Okey-dokey. It'll be ready by 5:00.

270
00:14:39,713 --> 00:14:42,215
-5:00 sharp.
-Okay. Thanks!

271
00:14:43,049 --> 00:14:45,552
5:00? But Grandma won't be back in time.

272
00:14:45,635 --> 00:14:48,096
That's why we're going to make it ourselves.

273
00:14:48,638 --> 00:14:51,266
But what do you know about making cakes?

274
00:14:51,307 --> 00:14:55,145
How hard can it be?
I've been eating 'em my whole life.

275
00:14:57,605 --> 00:14:59,983
First off, a little vanilla.

276
00:15:02,819 --> 00:15:04,279
And flour.

277
00:15:04,571 --> 00:15:05,613
(CHUCKLES)

278
00:15:07,782 --> 00:15:09,325
Don't forget the sugar.

279
00:15:09,659 --> 00:15:12,662
More. More. Just a little more.

280
00:15:14,497 --> 00:15:15,582
(CHUCKLES)

281
00:15:15,915 --> 00:15:16,958
Perfect.

282
00:15:17,584 --> 00:15:19,627
Isn't this gonna be a little too sweet?

283
00:15:19,669 --> 00:15:23,465
No such thing as
too sweet when you're talking about cakes.

284
00:15:23,673 --> 00:15:25,008
Don't forget the eggs.

285
00:15:26,843 --> 00:15:29,346
Had to go out to
the garage to find it, but I got the oil.

286
00:15:29,429 --> 00:15:32,515
Hey. As long as it says oil, it'll do the trick.

287
00:15:36,770 --> 00:15:37,812
(WHINES)

288
00:15:37,854 --> 00:15:39,314
STYMIE: What's that?
SPANKY: Yeast.

289
00:15:39,439 --> 00:15:41,024
It's something my mom always puts in cakes.

290
00:15:41,149 --> 00:15:43,193
It makes the cake grow big.

291
00:15:43,318 --> 00:15:45,862
Well, this woman wanted a big cake.
So let's put it all in.

292
00:15:46,696 --> 00:15:48,198
MARY ANN: Got the main ingredient.

293
00:15:55,205 --> 00:15:59,709
Our red velvet cakes
are made with 100% pure red velvet.

294
00:15:59,834 --> 00:16:01,378
And how!

295
00:16:01,461 --> 00:16:02,504
(BARKS)

296
00:16:05,882 --> 00:16:08,301
Mmm-mmm-mmm.

297
00:16:08,635 --> 00:16:09,678
Mmm.

298
00:16:09,803 --> 00:16:14,140
I sure could go
for one of those delicious-looking cupcakes.

299
00:16:14,224 --> 00:16:16,559
But Spanky says
we can't eat the merchandise.

300
00:16:16,685 --> 00:16:17,894
We're not gonna eat them,

301
00:16:18,019 --> 00:16:20,980
we're just gonna
test them out to make sure they're still good.

302
00:16:25,652 --> 00:16:26,861
Well, this one's good.

303
00:16:26,903 --> 00:16:28,405
This one, too.

304
00:16:28,530 --> 00:16:29,823
Better test the rest.

305
00:16:30,156 --> 00:16:31,533
Good idea.

306
00:16:39,874 --> 00:16:42,252
This is gonna be some cake.

307
00:16:42,335 --> 00:16:43,920
ALL: Yeah.

308
00:16:49,384 --> 00:16:52,095
BANK OFFICER: Well,
I've reviewed your paperwork, Mrs. Larson,

309
00:16:52,178 --> 00:16:53,888
and I'm very sorry,

310
00:16:53,930 --> 00:16:58,226
but you owe this bank $10,000,
and it is past due.

311
00:16:58,268 --> 00:17:02,272
You must pay it back
or we will be forced to take away your bakery.

312
00:17:02,939 --> 00:17:06,901
Oh. Would you like to
try one of my chocolate chip cookies?

313
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:08,528
Ooh.

314
00:17:08,611 --> 00:17:11,448
No. No, I'm trying to watch my calories.

315
00:17:12,449 --> 00:17:14,409
Now, about the loan.

316
00:17:14,451 --> 00:17:16,911
Well, I don't think one would hurt.

317
00:17:16,953 --> 00:17:18,788
I mean, they're from my bakery,

318
00:17:18,913 --> 00:17:22,292
and you would just be doing due diligence.

319
00:17:30,467 --> 00:17:32,927
I'm sorry about not paying back the money,

320
00:17:32,969 --> 00:17:35,805
but if you could
just give me a little bit more time.

321
00:17:36,056 --> 00:17:37,891
Mmm...

322
00:17:38,224 --> 00:17:39,768
Oh, my gosh.

323
00:17:39,809 --> 00:17:42,270
That's the best
chocolate chip cookie I've ever had.

324
00:17:42,312 --> 00:17:44,981
It's got just the right crunchy to chewy ratio.

325
00:17:45,065 --> 00:17:47,233
Ooh, I'm so glad you like them.

326
00:17:47,317 --> 00:17:48,443
This isn't a cookie.

327
00:17:49,277 --> 00:17:50,653
It's nirvana.

328
00:17:50,779 --> 00:17:52,155
It's bliss.

329
00:17:52,572 --> 00:17:53,656
It's a warm puppy.

330
00:17:53,740 --> 00:17:56,826
-(GIGGLES)
-It's sleeping late on a summer morning,

331
00:17:56,951 --> 00:17:59,996
or walking barefoot on the beach at sunset.

332
00:18:00,997 --> 00:18:02,749
If this cookie were a woman,
I would ask it to marry me.

333
00:18:02,832 --> 00:18:05,001
You see? With a cookie like this,

334
00:18:05,126 --> 00:18:07,295
business is just bound to pick up.

335
00:18:07,337 --> 00:18:11,633
And I'm sure I could
pay back the $10,000 in two months.

336
00:18:12,175 --> 00:18:14,969
-Would you like another one?
-Yes. What? No.

337
00:18:15,011 --> 00:18:17,847
Look, I'm sorry, Mrs. Larson,
but you've already had three extensions.

338
00:18:17,931 --> 00:18:19,182
My hands are tied.

339
00:18:19,307 --> 00:18:22,686
You simply must
pay back the $10,000 by the end of the month.

340
00:18:22,769 --> 00:18:24,938
But that's only two weeks away.

341
00:18:25,021 --> 00:18:27,315
-Maybe it's time you retired.
-Oh.

342
00:18:27,357 --> 00:18:28,525
Yes, sell the bakery.

343
00:18:28,692 --> 00:18:30,026
Do what makes you happy.

344
00:18:31,111 --> 00:18:33,530
I'm happiest when I'm baking.

345
00:18:34,155 --> 00:18:35,532
Well...

346
00:18:42,247 --> 00:18:43,498
Do you mind?

347
00:18:44,374 --> 00:18:46,334
They're just so good.

348
00:18:52,841 --> 00:18:54,050
(BELCHES)

349
00:18:54,092 --> 00:18:56,344
Our work here is done.

350
00:18:56,386 --> 00:18:58,263
What shall we have for dessert?

351
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:00,223
Hmm? More!

352
00:19:00,515 --> 00:19:02,058
(BOTH BELCHING)

353
00:19:02,434 --> 00:19:05,186
I can't wait to
see the expression on Grandma's face

354
00:19:05,228 --> 00:19:08,189
when she sees
how we made a cake on our own.

355
00:19:08,231 --> 00:19:09,274
(RUMBLING)

356
00:19:15,071 --> 00:19:17,449
I don't like the sound of that.

357
00:19:17,615 --> 00:19:18,742
Me neither.

358
00:19:22,412 --> 00:19:24,080
Is it supposed to be doing that?

359
00:19:26,249 --> 00:19:27,584
(RUMBLING)

360
00:19:30,587 --> 00:19:32,130
What was that?

361
00:19:32,255 --> 00:19:34,758
Sounds like a moose trying to sing.

362
00:19:34,883 --> 00:19:36,593
Maybe it's Alfalfa.

363
00:19:36,718 --> 00:19:39,137
Come on, let's go check it out.

364
00:19:41,056 --> 00:19:42,599
Take cover!

365
00:19:49,397 --> 00:19:50,440
(WHIMPERS)

366
00:19:58,823 --> 00:19:59,908
(GASPING)

367
00:20:08,458 --> 00:20:10,460
(WHIMPERING)

368
00:20:15,965 --> 00:20:17,133
Kids?

369
00:20:17,634 --> 00:20:20,679
I think we used a teeny bit too much yeast!

370
00:20:21,137 --> 00:20:22,430
You think?

371
00:20:22,472 --> 00:20:23,682
STYMIE: What do we do?

372
00:20:23,807 --> 00:20:26,476
Don't worry. I'll just take some air out of it.

373
00:20:27,352 --> 00:20:28,812
-STYMIE: Uh-oh.
-(WHINES)

374
00:20:29,854 --> 00:20:31,481
-Kids?
-(EXPLOSION)

375
00:20:33,983 --> 00:20:35,402
Oh. Are you all right?

376
00:20:35,527 --> 00:20:36,945
(UTENSIL CLATTERING)

377
00:20:36,986 --> 00:20:39,489
Oh, my goodness.

378
00:20:39,614 --> 00:20:41,324
What happened?

379
00:20:44,494 --> 00:20:46,162
-(WHINES)
-(DINGS)

380
00:20:46,705 --> 00:20:48,832
Guess that means the cake's ready.

381
00:20:56,798 --> 00:20:58,550
What a mess you are.

382
00:20:58,675 --> 00:21:01,678
-It was a delicious mess.
-Oh, good.

383
00:21:02,512 --> 00:21:05,056
-What's Waldo doing here?
-Where?

384
00:21:06,057 --> 00:21:07,392
(GROANS)

385
00:21:11,354 --> 00:21:12,397
Oh.

386
00:21:12,856 --> 00:21:15,358
Oh, this is sweet.

387
00:21:15,734 --> 00:21:16,818
Oh.

388
00:21:17,193 --> 00:21:18,403
Mrs. Larson?

389
00:21:18,653 --> 00:21:21,489
Ray Kaye, but my friends call me Big Ray,

390
00:21:21,531 --> 00:21:23,033
because I think big.

391
00:21:23,158 --> 00:21:25,035
Well, what can I do for you, Mr. Kaye?

392
00:21:25,160 --> 00:21:28,663
No, no, no. It's what can I do for you.

393
00:21:28,830 --> 00:21:31,666
I understand that your property here,
its loan is coming due.

394
00:21:31,708 --> 00:21:34,210
And I'm here to offer you
a business proposition.

395
00:21:34,419 --> 00:21:37,047
And I'm consulting on the deal.

396
00:21:37,088 --> 00:21:38,423
He's so cute.

397
00:21:38,548 --> 00:21:43,887
I'm gonna offer you
$100,000 here and now if you sell it to me.

398
00:21:44,429 --> 00:21:45,764
RASCALS: $100,000!

399
00:21:45,889 --> 00:21:47,766
That's a lot of money.

400
00:21:48,183 --> 00:21:51,269
Now, that's a...
That's a lot of cute little people.

401
00:21:51,394 --> 00:21:53,021
You wanna buy my bakery?

402
00:21:53,396 --> 00:21:54,731
Yes, I do.

403
00:21:54,939 --> 00:21:56,733
-Why?
-Progress.

404
00:21:56,858 --> 00:21:59,402
Look, here is your bakery right now.

405
00:21:59,444 --> 00:22:01,946
And as you can see, it's old, it's rundown,

406
00:22:02,072 --> 00:22:04,741
it's desperately in need of a face-lift.
And here's my plan.

407
00:22:04,783 --> 00:22:08,411
We're gonna tear it all down
and then in its place, this.

408
00:22:09,579 --> 00:22:11,790
Say, what happened to Grandma's bakery?

409
00:22:11,915 --> 00:22:13,375
RASCALS: Yeah!

410
00:22:13,416 --> 00:22:15,752
Who's that? It's you again. Little short stack.

411
00:22:15,919 --> 00:22:19,255
I'll tell you what happened.
Mixed-use development.

412
00:22:19,381 --> 00:22:23,093
Retail stores, office space, luxury apartments.
All very modern.

413
00:22:23,218 --> 00:22:24,386
A mall?

414
00:22:24,469 --> 00:22:26,471
Oh, no, no, no.

415
00:22:26,596 --> 00:22:29,933
Not a mall. A Big Ray's Malltopia.

416
00:22:30,058 --> 00:22:32,102
All glass and steel.
It's gonna kick this sleepy city

417
00:22:32,143 --> 00:22:33,770
right in the 21st century.

418
00:22:33,895 --> 00:22:36,439
What, you're just gonna tear down my bakery?

419
00:22:37,065 --> 00:22:38,274
No, no, no, no, no.

420
00:22:38,316 --> 00:22:41,945
No, I wanna offer you a very fair price,

421
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:43,488
then tear it down.

422
00:22:43,613 --> 00:22:44,948
WALDO: What about the tree house, Dad?

423
00:22:45,073 --> 00:22:46,282
No, don't worry about the tree house, Waldo.

424
00:22:46,324 --> 00:22:47,742
We'll uproot the tree and the tree house,

425
00:22:47,784 --> 00:22:50,078
and we'll have it moved
right into our backyard.

426
00:22:50,120 --> 00:22:51,663
That's our tree house.

427
00:22:51,788 --> 00:22:53,581
RASCALS: Yeah!

428
00:22:53,790 --> 00:22:55,917
Not after my dad buys it.

429
00:22:55,959 --> 00:22:57,961
Then it will be my tree house.

430
00:22:58,586 --> 00:22:59,671
Members only.

431
00:23:00,130 --> 00:23:03,800
And none of you will be members.

432
00:23:03,925 --> 00:23:05,427
(CHUCKLES) Isn't he cute?

433
00:23:05,468 --> 00:23:09,973
I'm sorry, Mr. Kaye,
but I can't imagine closing this place. No.

434
00:23:10,473 --> 00:23:13,268
See, my grandparents started this business.

435
00:23:13,810 --> 00:23:16,646
Oh, well, you can sell it to me,
or lose it to the bank in two weeks.

436
00:23:16,771 --> 00:23:18,982
Unless, of course, I don't know,

437
00:23:19,107 --> 00:23:21,276
you got $10,000 lying around. No.

438
00:23:21,776 --> 00:23:23,820
Look, you're gonna get a much better deal

439
00:23:23,862 --> 00:23:25,613
from me than you will from the bank.

440
00:23:25,655 --> 00:23:27,782
Well, I have two weeks to raise the money.

441
00:23:28,033 --> 00:23:29,993
Until then, I won't sell.

442
00:23:30,035 --> 00:23:32,787
Well, I'm just trying to be the good guy here.

443
00:23:33,538 --> 00:23:35,999
All right. Have it your way.

444
00:23:36,541 --> 00:23:38,376
Two weeks. Bye-bye.

445
00:23:40,295 --> 00:23:44,841
Grandma, you owe the bank $10,000?

446
00:23:44,966 --> 00:23:46,009
Yes.

447
00:23:47,344 --> 00:23:48,470
I know.

448
00:23:48,511 --> 00:23:49,804
When we win the talent show, Grandma,

449
00:23:49,846 --> 00:23:52,182
we'll just give you the $10,000.

450
00:23:52,307 --> 00:23:53,391
(CHUCKLES) Oh.

451
00:23:53,516 --> 00:23:55,852
ALFALFA: Yeah. That's first prize.

452
00:23:55,894 --> 00:23:58,813
Did you hear
what we sounded like this afternoon?

453
00:23:58,855 --> 00:23:59,981
We were terrible.

454
00:24:00,023 --> 00:24:01,232
Speak for yourself.

455
00:24:01,358 --> 00:24:02,859
She's right.

456
00:24:03,234 --> 00:24:05,528
We'll never win the talent show.

457
00:24:06,196 --> 00:24:07,489
Sorry, Grandma.

458
00:24:07,530 --> 00:24:09,157
GRANDMA: That's okay, kids.

459
00:24:09,199 --> 00:24:13,870
Please excuse me,
but I think I'm gonna clean up the kitchen

460
00:24:13,953 --> 00:24:16,790
while I still have a kitchen to clean.

461
00:24:23,672 --> 00:24:25,048
What are we gonna do?

462
00:24:25,173 --> 00:24:27,384
Not only will Grandma lose her bakery,

463
00:24:27,467 --> 00:24:30,053
but we're gonna lose our tree house to Waldo.

464
00:24:30,136 --> 00:24:31,179
SPANKY: Hold on.

465
00:24:34,849 --> 00:24:36,893
I have a great idea

466
00:24:37,477 --> 00:24:41,815
and I'm gonna give it to you in one word.

467
00:24:42,190 --> 00:24:43,733
Jobs.

468
00:24:57,747 --> 00:24:59,499
Whoa, whoa, whoa...

469
00:25:06,756 --> 00:25:07,841
(BARKING)

470
00:25:17,100 --> 00:25:18,393
MARY ANN: Hey, guys.

471
00:25:20,770 --> 00:25:22,188
OFFICER KENNEDY: Thank you!

472
00:25:22,939 --> 00:25:25,025
Oh, come on!

473
00:25:45,378 --> 00:25:46,796
Mr. Kaye!

474
00:25:47,881 --> 00:25:49,716
Here they are, gentlemen.

475
00:25:50,091 --> 00:25:51,134
Your new caddies.

476
00:25:51,718 --> 00:25:53,303
Is this some kind of a joke?

477
00:25:53,386 --> 00:25:55,472
I'm sorry,
but three of my caddies called in sick.

478
00:25:55,555 --> 00:25:57,223
They're all I've got right now.

479
00:25:58,475 --> 00:26:00,977
Haven't I seen you
two guys somewhere before?

480
00:26:02,270 --> 00:26:04,397
Where would you have seen us before?

481
00:26:04,481 --> 00:26:06,649
Yeah, we travel in different social circles.

482
00:26:06,816 --> 00:26:08,985
I don't know. They're awful short.

483
00:26:09,819 --> 00:26:12,280
Hey, as long as they can carry a bag,
what difference does it make?

484
00:26:13,156 --> 00:26:15,575
Okay, let's go. We're late.
Come on, grab the bags.

485
00:26:16,659 --> 00:26:19,120
Now you two do exactly what Mr. Kaye says

486
00:26:19,162 --> 00:26:21,623
or you're out of a job. Understand?

487
00:26:21,664 --> 00:26:23,124
BOTH: Yes, sir.

488
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:26,503
Oh, Edgar, how did you
manage having lunch here?

489
00:26:26,628 --> 00:26:28,254
You're not even a member of this club.

490
00:26:28,338 --> 00:26:30,674
Let's just say
I have a few friends in high places.

491
00:26:30,757 --> 00:26:31,841
Oh, you mean the Chief?

492
00:26:31,966 --> 00:26:33,677
Yep, that's one.

493
00:26:33,802 --> 00:26:35,512
Ooh, fancy.

494
00:26:35,929 --> 00:26:37,013
(PANTING)

495
00:26:37,097 --> 00:26:41,184
Man, this working
for a living sure is a lot of work.

496
00:26:41,518 --> 00:26:44,437
Yeah, I think
I'm more cut out for executive work.

497
00:26:44,521 --> 00:26:46,523
You know, with a corner office.

498
00:26:46,606 --> 00:26:47,691
You said it, pal.

499
00:26:50,485 --> 00:26:52,362
Oh, Ed, this is lovely.

500
00:26:52,487 --> 00:26:54,531
Well, it is a special occasion.

501
00:26:54,823 --> 00:26:56,533
After all, we've been dating for

502
00:26:56,658 --> 00:26:59,494
one year, five months, three
weeks, four days and nine hours.

503
00:26:59,703 --> 00:27:01,329
But who's counting.
(CHUCKLES)

504
00:27:03,373 --> 00:27:05,875
Well, every minute of it has been wonderful.

505
00:27:06,334 --> 00:27:08,044
It has, hasn't it?

506
00:27:08,670 --> 00:27:10,296
(SPANKY AND ALFALFA GIGGLING)

507
00:27:11,381 --> 00:27:13,008
SPANKY: Who does he think he is, a pro?

508
